It's a good start but I feel there's plenty to improve. Don't feel bad, we've all had to start somewhere. Anyway, here's the stuff I found obvious.

>Before an author write they need to ask themselves why they write this. By that I refer to if you were to write something would it effect the overall story and if not, it's probably best to remove it. I found this quite often with clauses that could be removed to make the story flow better.
>The armouring up scene dragged on for way too long, I feel it could be described in shorter to keep the pace.
>Sentences are often way too long with way too many commas. What I suggest is have short snappy sentences with no commas for action and longer sentences for calm. I would recommend 2 commas maximum unless you're listing.
>The backstory of Anon Wasser goes on for a long time and probably should have stopped at his farm being attacked by beastmen. This info dump can dissuade readers and breaks the flow of the story for too long. I feel Anon's backstory should be described over time in short bursts as it becomes easier for the reader to digest.
>Proofreading is important, I see lots of gramma and spelling mistakes. I suggest grammarly or a free online spell checker. When proof reading I suggest do it then take a break and do it again.

Don't take all of this too negatively, I started like this too and I'm offering my help for you to improve. If you want me to beta read and help you improve you can contact me at my pastebin:

https://pastebin.com/u/Vani11aS33d

Keep it up.

>Proofreading is important, I see lots of gramma and spelling mistakes. I suggest grammarly or a free online spell checker. When proof reading I suggest do it then take a break and do it again.
I'm gonna jump in here with some advice that helped me a great deal.
When you're finished writing your piece, take a break. Get a snack, get up and stretch, watch a YouTube video - just get away from it for a few minutes.
Then, sit back down and proofread your own work - ALOUD.
I'm dead serious - Audiobook that motherfucker.
Speaking your way through something you've written makes grammar mistakes, spelling errors, awkward phrasing and other problems fucking leap out at you. You'll be amazed how this cleans up your work.

It depends on the character. With raptors, the "feral look" is in the posture and the shape of the spine, which owes a lot to how well their tails are presented in artwork. If you've an artist who handles the anatomical details well, and know to take that into account in gesture and pose, you'll find that golden mean between feral/humanoid comes naturally. It really does. After that, it falls to expression - in all honesty, just how h u m a n an anthro raptor (and most scalies) looks depends a lot on how well her gestures and expressions translate to comprehensible human emotions.
>>31003364

I can see where a good many of her movements would call her tail into action (like raptor-running), and that's thanks to the way he handles her anatomy.
